Abstract = {The Podostemaceae are a large family (48 genera and 270 species) of
   aquatic flowering plants that grow attached to rocks and boulders
   exclusively in running water or under cataracts in the tropical and
   subtropical regions of the Old World and the New World. The family is
   divided into two subfamilies-the Tristichoideae and the Podostemoideae.
   The plants of this family are characterized by a set of unusual
   morphological, anatomical, embryological, developmental and evolutionary
   features not found in such a combination in any other group of
   angiosperms.
   The podostemad plant body is thalloid and lacks air spaces
   characteristic of aquatic macrophytes. It deviates markedly from the
   classical root shoot (CRS) model of typical angiosperms. Evolutionary
   forces seem to have modified these plants to such an extent that
   morphological entities such as root, stem and leaf cannot be applied
   with 1:1 homology, leading to `fuzzy morphology'. The organ identity of
   the thallus and its components has been a subject of much dispute ever
   since the first podostemad was discovered. The prevalence of high
   plasticity, perplexing polymorphism and marked structural reductionism
   make the taxonomic delimitation a despairing experience. The genus
   Polypleurum has so many forms that each one of them has been given the
   status of a species.
   Podostemaceae have often been cited as an embryological family because
   of absence of antipodal cells, triple fusion, endosperm, and occurrence
   of a 4-nucleate mature embryo sac, single fertilization and a
   pseudo-embryo sac. With increasing interest in the search for lineages
   of the ancient flowering plants, the simple module of the podostemad
   embryo sac with a single fertilization offers an interesting system for
   evolutionary studies. Double fertilization is considered a ubiquitous,
   defining, ancestral feature of angiosperms. Nevertheless, its absence in
   all the podostemads investigated so far suggests either a polyphyletic
   origin of angiosperms or embryological reductionism. The mature
   podostemad embryo is highly simplified as it lacks an identifiable shoot
   apical meristem and a root apical meristem. In the absence of the two
   apical growing points, how, when and from where does a thalloid plant
   body arise has been a subject of our research for many years. As it is
   almost impossible to investigate seed germination in the environment of
   a turbulent river, we conducted studies using an aseptic method with a
   modified nutrient medium. Five members of Podostemoideae studied by us
   show that the radicular pole remains quiescent. A shoot apical meristem
   is initiated at the putative plumular region that eventually
   differentiates a highly reduced, determinate primary axis. The main
   plant body arises as a lateral outgrowth of the shoot apical meristem
   that subsequently ruptures the hypocotyl to emerge and spread
   diageotropically on the substratum. in two species namely- Polypleurum
   stylosum and Indotristicha ramosissima, plants have been grown to
   maturity and induced to flower under experimental stress conditions.
   In nature the podostemads complete their vegetative phase and initiate
   flowering while they are still submerged. Pollination and fruit
   formation generally occur above water. Our research group has studied
   the reproductive biology and traced pollination strategies beginning
   from autogamy under aerial conditions to cleistogamy under submerged
   situation. Contrary to the general condition noticed in aquatic
   angiosperms,. seed set is very high. Some taxonomic literature points to
   the affinities of the Podostemaceae with Rosaceae, Saxifragaceae,
   Hydrostachyclaceae and Crassulaceae. Interestingly, the recent
   phylogenetic studies using rbcL data suggest a possible sister group
   relationship of Podostemaceae (within Malphigiales clade) to
   Crassulaceae (Saxifragales).},
